value.value: A process by which the range of hosts which a virus can bind and infect is changed. Examples include phages that switch between types of fibers via the action of a virally encoded invertase.
Catalysis of the reaction: nucleoside triphosphate + RNA(n) = diphosphate + RNA(n+1); the addition of a terminal nucleotide to an RNA molecule in the absence of a nucleic acid template.

A non-membrane bound, electron dense structure associated that extends perpendicular to the presynaptic membrane in ribbon synapses. The ribbon's surface is studded with small particles to which synaptic vesicles tether via fine filaments. The tethered vesicles function as a pool, several fold greater than the docked pool available for fast release, which supports sustained release of vesicles. Synaptic ribbons may be plate like or spherical.
An electron dense structure that anchors a synaptic ribbon to the presynaptic membrane.
A ribbon synpase of an auditory hair cell of the cochlear. These ribbon synapses contain spherical synaptic ribbons and lack and arciform density.
A ribbon synapse between a retinal photoreceptor cell (rod or cone) and a retinal bipolar cell. These contain a plate-like synaptic ribbon.
A synapse between the Schaffer collateral axon of a CA3 pyramidal cell and a CA1 pyramidal cell.

label.value: hippocampal mossy fiber to CA3 synapse

value.value: One of the giant synapses that form between the mossy fiber axons of dentate gyrus granule cells and the large complex spines of CA3 pyramidal cells. It consists of a giant bouton known as the mossy fiber expansion, synapsed to the complex, multiheaded spine (thorny excresence) of a CA3 pyramidal cell.
Any subdivision of a chromosome along its length.

definition.value: Chromosomal regions include parts that are not part of the chromatin. Examples include the kinetochore.

label.value: parallel fiber to Purkinje cell synapse

value.value: An excitatory synapse formed by the parallel fibers of granule cells synapsing onto the dendrites of Purkinje cells.

The process by which a virus switches on its replication cycle in an infected cell. The process is typically controlled by a genetic switch controlled by environmental factors such as cell type, cell shape, the availability of nutrients, superinfection or exposure of infected cells to UV or various chemical stimuli.
A synapse that uses glycine as a neurotransmitter.
A synapse that uses dopamine as a neurotransmitter.
A synapse that uses noradrenaline as a neurotransmitter.
Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of the synaptic vesicle cycle.

label.value: regulation of synaptic vesicle budding from presynaptic endocytic zone membrane

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of synaptic vesicle budding from presynaptic endocytic zone membrane.

label.value: inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate receptor activity involved in regulation of postsynaptic cytosolic calcium levels

value.value: Any inositol 1,4,5-trisphosphate receptor activity that is involved in regulation of postsynaptic cytosolic calcium ion concentration.

label.value: regulation of neurotransmitter receptor localization to postsynaptic specialization membrane

value.value: Any process that modulates the frequency, rate or extent of neurotransmitter receptor localization to postsynaptic specialization membrane.

label.value: ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel activity involved in regulation of postsynaptic cytosolic calcium levels

value.value: Any ryanodine-sensitive calcium-release channel activity that is involved in regulation of postsynaptic cytosolic calcium ion concentration.
The aggregation, arrangement and bonding together of a set of components to form a postsynaptic specialization, a region that lies adjacent to the cytoplasmic face of the postsynaptic membrane.

label.value: structural constituent of presynaptic actin cytoskeleton

value.value: The action of a molecule that contributes to the structural integrity of a presynaptic actin cytoskeleton.
The active transport of neurotransmitters into a synaptic vesicle. This import is fuelled by an electrochemical gradient across the vesicle membrane, established by the action of proton pumps.
The directed movement of adenine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: calcium ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of calcium ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of a carbohydrate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: copper ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of copper ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: iron ion import across cell outer membrane

value.value: The directed movement of iron ions from outside of a cell, across the cell outer membrane and into the periplasmic space.
The directed movement of D-glucose from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of glutathione from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of guanine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: iron ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of iron ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of L-glutamate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of malate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: malonic acid import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of malonic acid from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: nickel cation import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of nickel cations from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of pantothenate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of serine from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.

label.value: sodium ion import across plasma membrane

value.value: The directed movement of sodium ions from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of succinate from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
The directed movement of uracil from outside of a cell, across the plasma membrane and into the cytosol.
Division of a stem cell during which it retains its identity and buds off a daughter cell with a new identity.
A myofibril of a skeletal muscle fiber.

Symmetric division of a stem cell to produce two stem cells of the same type as the parent. Symmetric stem cell division is necessary for amplification of stem cell populations in the absence of sources of stem cells external to an existing population.

definition.value: Examples include the self-renewal of spermatogonial stem cells and (some) division during amplification of skeletal muscle satellite cell populations.

value.value: Cell division in which both daughter cells are of the same type.

label.value: symmetric division of skeletal muscle satellite stem cell

value.value: The symmetric division of a skeletal muscle satellite stem cell, resulting in two skeletal muscle satellite stem cells. This process is involved in amplification of the pool of these cells.
Any process by which the numbers of cells of a particular type or in a tissue are maintained.
The self-renewing division of a germline stem cell, to produce a daughter stem cell and a daughter germ cell which will divide to form one or more gametes.
Division of a germline stem cell to produce two germline stem cells of the same type as the parent.

label.value: male germline stem cell symmetric division

value.value: The symmetric division of a male germline stem cell to produce two male germline stem cells. An example of this is found in mammalian spermatogonial stem cells, some proportion of which divide symmetrically, so amplifying the population. The choice between asymmetric and symmetric division in this case appears to be internal and stochastic.

label.value: skeletal muscle satellite stem cell maintenance involved in skeletal muscle regeneration

value.value: Any process by which the number of skeletal muscle satellite stem cells in a skeletal muscle is maintained during skeletal muscle regeneration. There are at least two mechanisms by which this is achieved. Skeletal muscle satellite stem cell asymmetric division ensures satellite stem cell numbers are kept constant. Symmetric division of these cells amplifies the number of skeletal muscle satellite stem cells.
